                <head>49. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On January 18, 1971, President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> sent
                    a memorandum to the Secretaries of State, Treasury, Agriculture, Commerce, and
                    Labor; the Director of the Office of Management and Budget; the Chairman of the
                    Council of Economic Advisers; the President’s Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs; the Executive Director of the Domestic Council; and the Special Trade
                    Representative establishing a Council on International Economic Policy (<gloss
                        target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss>). The President would chair the Council (in
                    his absence the Secretary of State would chair the meetings), and the addressees
                    of the memorandum were the Council’s members. The President’s memorandum was
                    released to the public on January 19; see <hi rend="italic">Public Papers of the
                        Presidents of the United States: <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Richard M.
                            Nixon</persName>, 1971,</hi> pages 40-41. The memorandum and additional
                    documentation on the establishment of the <gloss target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss>
                    are scheduled for publication in a forthcoming <hi rend="italic">Foreign
                        Relations</hi> volume on the Organization and Management of Foreign Policy.
                        <persName corresp="#p_PPG1">Peter Peterson</persName> was named the first
                    Director of the <gloss target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss>.</p>
                <pb facs="0149" n="121" xml:id="pg_121"/>
                <p>On February 1 Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName>
                    requested that the Department of Defense be represented on the <gloss
                        target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss>, in part because of the balance-of-payments
                    linkage with burden-sharing and offset negotiations. (Memorandum from Laird to
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, February 1; National
                    Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials,
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Agency Files, Box 226, <gloss
                        target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> 12/1/70-2/23/71) In a February 19 memorandum to
                    White House Staff Assistant John Campbell, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> noted that <persName corresp="#p_LMR2"
                        >Laird</persName>’s request was reasonable but doubted the <gloss
                        target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss> would have sufficient military or security
                    business to warrant a permanent Defense Department member. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> suggested getting Peterson’s opinion
                    before making a decision on <persName corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName>’s
                    request. (Ibid.) At least in part because of concerns about <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> control, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> on July 17 sent a memorandum to Peterson, who had some
                    sympathy with the idea, opposing Defense Department participation in the <gloss
                        target="#t_CIEP1">CIEP</gloss>. (Ibid., Box 218, <gloss target="#t_CIEP1"
                        >CIEP</gloss>) On August 9, however, <persName corresp="#p_PPG1"
                        >Peterson</persName> sent a memorandum to the <gloss target="#t_CIEP1"
                        >CIEP</gloss> members, including the Secretary of Defense, stating the
                    President’s decision that the Secretary of Defense should be a member of the
                    Council and that the Department of Defense would participate fully in the
                    Council’s work. (Ibid.)</p>
